description.plain: Miranda Lambert was born November 10, 1983 in Longview, Texas to Richard Lee and Beverly June Hughes Lambert.  She has a brother, Luke.  The 5'4" country music artist/songwriter gained fame as a finalist on the 2003 season of Nashville Star, where she finished in third place and later signed to Epic Records.  Miranda married Blake Shelton on May 14, 2011 but the couple divorced on July 20, 2015. Lambert is especially known for “The House that Built Me”, “White Liar” and “Kerosene”.

“Little Red Wagon” was released as the third single from Miranda Lambert’s fifth studio album, Platinum.  It was originally performed by Audra Mae on her 2012 album, Audra Mae & The Almighty Sound.

The songs lyrics riff on the Willie Nelson classic, “Won’t You Ride In My Little Red Wagon.”

How did Lambert first hear the song? She explains at Great American Country:

John Eddie is an artist who has come out on the road with us before and opened a few times. He called my tour manager three or four years ago and said, ‘Hey, tell Miranda about this girl Audra Mae, specifically her song ‘Little Red Wagon.’ I think she could rock it.



Lambert performed the song at the 2015 Grammy Awards. She’s also recorded an official music video.

description.plain: Miranda and Blake wrote this son about Blake’s brother who was killed in a car accident at the age of 24. Blake was 14 at the time. It was in December, but the song references the fact that it is still hard to deal with his death no matter that it isn’t the anniversary or anything. His parent’s gave Blake all of his brother’s music and Blake would listen to the records over and over remembering his brother and feeling him there. I know you didn’t mean to give them to me is because it was an accident and it makes Blake mad that he’s gone, that he doesn’t get to see him any more. How dare you leave me? His Dad is referenced in an interview saying It isn’t something you ever get over, you just get used to it.

description.plain:
“Highway Vagabond” is a song about the virtues of being a drifter.  While it certainly applies to the life of a traveling musician, it really speaks to all  those with a restless spirit.

The opening lines also encourage the listener to follow the beat of their own drum:  “I wanna go somewhere nobody knows. I wanna know somewhere nobody goes”, essentially telling us to follow our own dream, not those pushed on us by conventional thinkers.

description.plain:
Gunpowder & Lead is the first track and third single from Miranda Lambert’s second album, Crazy Ex-Girlfriend.

Lyrically, it talks about a crazy ex-boyfriend (pun intended) who mistreated her physically and mentally, so she decides to do something about it…by killing him.

In the US, it was moderately successful, reaching 52 on the Billboard Hot 100. However, it reached 7 on the Hot Country Songs chart, becoming her first top ten there. As of May 2014, it was certified double platinum (2,000,000 copies sold) by the RIAA.

description.plain:
“Kerosene” was the title song & third single released from Miranda Lambert’s 2005 debut album.

Even though Miranda wrote the song, she gave co-writer’s credit to singer Steve Earle after listeners noticed a similarity to his song “I Feel All Right”.

In an interview, she stated that she unconsciously copied the melody and structure of the song, saying:

I didn’t purposefully plagiarize his song, but unconsciously I copied it almost exactly. I guess I’d listened to it so much that I just kind of had it in there

The song became a hit for Miranda, peaking at #61 on the Billboard Hot 100 and #15 on Billboard’s Hot Country Songs chart in 2005.

White Liar is the second single from Miranda Lambert’s third album Revolution.

The song peaked at #38 on the Billboard Hot 100 and #2 on Billboard’s Hot Country Songs chart in 2009.

It has sold 1,202,000 copies in the United States and was nominated for three Country Music Awards.

Here’s an interesting fact: Miranda donated the original handwritten copy of “White Liar” to the Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum for public display behind a glass case.

Title track off Miranda’s fifth studio album. Platinum is a metal (below) but also a reference to a music industry recording sales certification system. In the US, an album is certified platinum after it sells 1,000,000 copies. Lambert’s Platinum hasn’t yet gone platinum – as of October 1, 2014, the album has sold 493,000 copies in the United States.
It also refers to her platinum blonde hair.

The album debuted at No. 1 on the Billboard 200, selling 180,000 copies in its first week and is Lambert’s first album to reach the top of the Billboard 200. It also marked her fifth consecutive No. 1 debut on the Top Country Albums Chart, making her the first artist in history to start her career with five No. 1 albums.

description.plain:
“Old Shit” is track eight on Miranda Lambert’s fifth album, Platinum.

Lambert and producer Frank Liddell roped East Nashville youngblood W.B. Givens in to sing duet on the track.

“When I recorded my last album,” Givens told Rolling Stone

we tracked it in my friend’s house. The vocals were cut in a walk-in closet. Going to Music Row and doing ‘Old Shit’ for Miranda’s album was different. It was a bizarre experience to walk into this giant live room, where you’ve got a Grammy-winning producer and audio engineer, and people are offering you room-temperature water for your voice.

Clearly Lambert, Liddell, and Givens didn’t record “Old Shit” on old shit…



Lyrically, the song expresses Lambert’s appreciation for old things – a nostalgic sentiment the singer has conveyed before, in songs like “Automatic”. Lambert carries on a country music tradition from classics like Merle Haggard’s “Are The Good Times Really Over For Good” and Tim McGraw’s “Back When”.

description.plain:
Dead Flowers was the lead single from Miranda Lambert’s third album Revolution.

The inspiration for the song is based on a personal experience from Miranda’s life. According to her:

I had some flowers that I got for Valentines Day in a vase on the kitchen table. I was going on the road so I had to throw them in the yard. They were just laying there and it was a really sad image. The song came to me right away and was one of those ones that kinda wrote itself."

The song peaked at #37 on Billboard’s Hot Country Songs chart in 2009, spending 16 weeks on the chart.

description.plain:
This is one of two cuts on Four The Record that Lambert penned solo, (the other one is “Safe”). It finds the singer debating whether to confess to her beau about her past or keep it to herself.

The song features the Country and Bluegrass singer, Patty Loveless. Lambert told Billboard magazine: “I was in Switzerland doing a festival last September and Patty was there. We got to spend some time together. She was already one of my heroes, but I definitely left there loving her even more. So as soon as I wrote it I was like, ‘I want Patty to sing on this song,’ and she did. It was a dream come true. It’s really special to me.”
